know, ecosystem of everything, the interface of Positron that's available, it's really

00:21:47.920 --> 00:21:54.239
quite impressive. And for you, you can try it yourself. If you just walk out here, take

00:21:54.239 --> 00:21:59.920
a few steps, we have laptops that are configured with Positron and Positron Assistant that

00:21:59.920 --> 00:22:04.800
you can try out. And, you know, the Positron team is there as well to answer any questions

00:22:04.800 --> 00:22:09.400
that you may have specifically about the layout or anything else. So I highly encourage you

00:22:09.400 --> 00:22:14.640
to try it. I did also want to give a shout out to my colleagues, Sharon Wing and Sam

00:22:14.640 --> 00:22:19.560
Edwards who developed this demo that I used. So thank you so much. It was a lot of fun

00:22:19.560 --> 00:22:26.000
to work with it. Last thing I want to mention is you might be thinking, wait a second, that

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:31.560
wasn't the actual first five minutes, right? And you are absolutely correct. There are

00:22:31.560 --> 00:22:37.599
quite a few things that happened before this that I did not mention. You know, so, for

00:22:37.599 --> 00:22:43.000
example, downloading and installing Positron and downloading and installing R and Python.

00:22:43.000 --> 00:22:49.239
And I have a lot of key bindings and extensions that I've installed and downloaded because,

00:22:49.239 --> 00:22:54.160
you know, I've been working with Positron for a little while. And so absolutely correct.

00:22:54.160 --> 00:22:57.719
And if you want to learn more about this, you can come watch my demo, which I'm giving

00:22:57.719 --> 00:23:03.839
next Wednesday. It's online. And I would love to see you there if you want to learn more

00:23:03.959 --> 00:23:08.959
about these steps as well. And with that, thank you so much for watching. And we're

00:23:08.959 --> 00:23:10.959
happy to take any questions.

00:23:40.959 --> 00:23:57.079
Can everyone still hear on the microphone virtually? Okay. Awesome. Yeah. Great question.

00:23:57.079 --> 00:24:02.000
We get asked this a lot. This is maybe one of our most asked for features in Positron.

00:24:02.000 --> 00:24:10.719
Oh, sorry. Yeah. The question is will Corto inline output be supported in Positron eventually?

00:24:11.520 --> 00:24:19.040
Short answer, yes. Long answer, this is, yeah, one of our most asked for features. Basically

00:24:19.040 --> 00:24:25.520
due to the architecture of the way that Positron, the Corto extension, the visual editor, everything

00:24:25.520 --> 00:24:30.959
is set up. It's a really tough change. But we do know, you know, thinking about Jonathan's

00:24:30.959 --> 00:24:39.359
keynote talk yesterday, we want to be listening to our users. It won't be planned for this year,

00:24:39.359 --> 00:24:44.319
probably. But it will be coming. Because we know that this is kind of a blocker for

00:24:44.880 --> 00:24:49.359
some people who want to use Positron. I will highlight, too, that we have support for

00:24:51.040 --> 00:24:58.880
notebooks, which, you know, have inline output out of the box, basically. But, yeah, right now

00:24:58.880 --> 00:25:05.119
that's what you want if you want to be creating documents with inline output. Or just like we're

00:25:05.119 --> 00:25:08.800
still fine with you going back to RStudio if that's what you need to use that for.

00:25:10.160 --> 00:25:11.359
It's a great tool for that right now.

00:25:24.640 --> 00:25:31.920
Good question. Yes. So, it yes. So, Positron has a sort of different notion of projects where

00:25:31.920 --> 00:25:36.959
we call them workspaces. And you open up a folder, basically,

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:45.280
you open up the folder as a workspace, and then your file layout, you know, basically,

00:25:46.079 --> 00:25:51.439
you can have workspace specific settings and everything. I believe there's nothing,

00:25:51.439 --> 00:25:57.439
like, necessarily special about that Rproj file in Positron. So, you can open up a folder as an

00:25:57.520 --> 00:26:02.400
Rproj, basically. We do have documentation about this, too, if you're more interested

00:26:02.400 --> 00:26:07.280
than my high level answer. I'm a little bit more on the Python side, so I don't know exactly,

00:26:07.280 --> 00:26:11.439
like, all of the technical details about that. But, like, short answer is yes.

00:26:15.359 --> 00:26:16.719
Yes. You can talk to Davis later.

00:26:27.439 --> 00:26:36.880
The question was, is VS Code going to be continued to be in Workbench alongside Positron?

00:26:36.880 --> 00:26:40.640
The answer is yes. I think there's a lot that you can do in VS Code that's very good to do

00:26:40.640 --> 00:26:46.640
in VS Code. I still develop a lot of TypeScript in VS Code, because it's just, like, there are more

00:26:46.640 --> 00:26:52.319
extensions and things around that, personally. So, yeah, I mean, we know that there's a bunch

00:26:52.319 --> 00:26:56.000
of different uses for the different IDEs, and, yeah, we'll continue to offer VS Code in Workbench.

00:26:57.520 --> 00:27:14.479
Yeah, roadmap for other languages being first class supported in Positron. I will call out

00:27:14.479 --> 00:27:19.040
that you can edit, you know, SQL, you can see syntax highlighting and stuff like that right now,

00:27:19.680 --> 00:27:24.079
but it's not like we have a SQL console necessarily right now. I do think we're

00:27:24.079 --> 00:27:29.920
interested in more first class SQL support. I can't commit to any timelines, sadly,

00:27:29.920 --> 00:27:36.160
because we just don't know exactly what the timelines look like. SQL support, Julia support

00:27:36.160 --> 00:27:41.280
are both, like, very highly upvoted, and it's just kind of a question of, like, what our priorities

00:27:41.280 --> 00:27:45.839
are, what our capacity is as a team, you know, what kind of support we get from the community

00:27:45.839 --> 00:27:51.439
and, like, interest. So I can't commit to a roadmap. I also can't say that it'll be this

00:27:51.439 --> 00:27:56.079
year in 2025, but, yeah.

00:28:51.439 --> 00:28:59.119
Yeah. Here, let me give you the mic. The question was, do we plan to support any

00:28:59.119 --> 00:29:06.479
older versions of R? We support R 4.2 and above, which is at this point five versions of R,

00:29:07.359 --> 00:29:14.079
which is the same version policy as the tidyverse, and like Positron being a newer IDE,

00:29:14.079 --> 00:29:19.280
had the ability to say we're going to be using a little bit newer version of R,

00:29:19.920 --> 00:29:24.640
which does come with a number of improvements, like on, like, Windows you get UTF-8 natively

00:29:24.640 --> 00:29:29.119
out of the box, which is, like, a huge benefit and simplifies a whole bunch of things. So

00:29:29.119 --> 00:29:32.400
we will not, we have no plans to extend that further back. Yeah.

00:29:41.199 --> 00:29:44.400
Another question. You asked what my favorite feature of Positron is. I'm very biased,

00:29:44.400 --> 00:29:48.880
but I really like remote SSH. This is something you can do in VS Code, but we kind of doctored

00:29:48.880 --> 00:29:54.800
it up and made it better, in my opinion, for Positron, where you can, if you have SSH access

00:29:54.800 --> 00:30:01.359
to a remote machine, you can connect with the little bottom left button, connect to the host,

00:30:01.359 --> 00:30:05.359
the UI still lives on your laptop, but basically everything else is on your remote machine. So if

00:30:05.359 --> 00:30:10.479
it's a more powerful machine, you get access to the file system, the data, the, your R session

00:30:10.479 --> 00:30:16.400
or whatever is on that remote machine, and you can take advantage of the compute and stuff.

00:30:17.040 --> 00:30:21.199
I really like it. And as well, you can disconnect and reconnect as your code is running,

00:30:21.199 --> 00:30:25.199
which is a big feature that I don't think VS Code has. So that's what I like.

00:30:46.400 --> 00:30:58.160
Can a remote SSH, or sorry, a Workbench EC2 instance be used as that SSH host? I believe

00:30:58.160 --> 00:31:03.680
the answer is yes. I think they qualify for all of our technical requirements. I haven't

00:31:03.680 --> 00:31:10.560
personally tried it. And I also don't want to give advice that would like mess up your instance,

00:31:10.560 --> 00:31:14.000
but if you pay for Workbench, you know, you have support, so you can always open a ticket.

